        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Equivalency of input parameters acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Model inputs must be traceable to experimental measurements; fixture compliance must be accounted for. Both criteria met with documented cross-reference table."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison performed for all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) using both percent difference (<10% criterion) and the validation metric E/uval (<1.96 criterion). Results: stiffness 4.2%/0.81, yield force 6.7%/1.12, force at 40 mm 8.1%/1.44. All six acceptance criteria satisfied. Graphical force-displacement overlays provided for visual confirmation of agreement throughout the loading history.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/ac-output-comparison-noncannulated",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison acceptance criteria",
        "description": "All primary QoIs must satisfy percent difference < 10% AND E/uval < 1.96. All three QoIs satisfy both criteria."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "This factor assesses whether the QoIs selected for validation are relevant to the intended clinical or regulatory decision. In the present COU, the QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are mandated directly by ASTM F1717 and are the same quantities used in the 510(k) substantial equivalence determination. There is no discretionary QoI selection to evaluate — the standard defines the outputs, and the regulatory pathway requires them. Accordingly, this factor does not require a separate credibility gradation assessment; its adequacy is established by conformance to the ASTM standard and FDA guidance on spinal implant bench testing."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "This factor evaluates whether the validation scenario is sufficiently representative of the clinical COU to support extrapolation of model credibility. In this package, the validation scenario IS the COU: the FEA model is validated against the identical ASTM F1717 test configuration that constitutes the regulatory submission activity. There is no gap between the validation domain and the intended use domain because the model is not being applied outside the validated scenario. Therefore, a separate assessment of validation-to-COU relevance is not meaningful and this factor is marked not-applicable. If the model were subsequently applied to a different loading mode or implant geometry, this factor would require re-assessment."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/dec-noncannulated-cou1",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/fda-cdrh-osel-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The FEA model ensemble for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct is accepted as sufficiently credible for its intended use in the ASTM F1717 compression-bending regulatory submission. Eleven of thirteen V&V 40 factors were formally assessed; two factors (Relevance of QoIs and Relevance of validation activities to COU) were marked not-applicable with documented rationale because the validation scenario is identical to the COU and the QoIs are mandated by the applicable ASTM standard. Of the eleven assessed factors, ten achieved their required credibility level or higher. One factor — Test conditions — achieved Gradation 2 against a required Gradation 3, reflecting the limitation that only a single ASTM F1717 static loading condition was evaluated. This shortfall is accepted on the basis of (a) all three primary QoIs satisfying both the percent-difference (<10%) and validation metric (E/uval < 1.96) acceptance criteria with margin, (b) the single test condition being the standard regulatory benchmark for this device class, and (c) the medium model risk level and medium decision consequence not requiring multi-condition coverage for initial 510(k) clearance. The offset rationale is formally documented. Provenance is complete from raw experimental data through FEA outputs to this decision record.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z",
    "hasOffsetRationale": [
      {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/offset/offset-test-conditions-noncannulated",
        "type": "OffsetRationale",
        "name": "Offset rationale for Test conditions shortfall",
        "refersToFactor": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/test-conditions-noncannulated",
        "justification": "The Test conditions factor achieved Gradation 2 (single standardized condition) against a required Gradation 3 (multiple conditions spanning the operating envelope). This shortfall is offset by three converging lines of evidence: (1) all three QoIs satisfy both acceptance criteria (percent difference < 10% and E/uval < 1.96) with the most conservative QoI (force at 40 mm) achieving E/uval = 1.44, providing a 26% margin before the 1.96 threshold; (2) the ASTM F1717 static compression-bending configuration is the sole regulatory test condition specified for this device class, meaning additional conditions are outside the defined COU scope; and (3) the medium model risk level (MRL 3) and medium decision consequence together place this assessment in a risk tier where a single validated condition is consistent with FDA-accepted practice for Class II spinal implant submissions. Dynamic and fatigue loading conditions are explicitly scoped out of this COU and would require separate credibility assessments."
      },
      {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/dec-noncannulated-cou1/offset/test-conditions",
        "type": "OffsetRationale",
        "refersToFactor": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/dec-noncannulated-cou1/factor/test-conditions",
        "justification": "Placeholder offset rationale (Phase 2.5 v0.5.11 corpus regen) for 'Test conditions' factor shortfall on this Accepted decision. The W-AR-02 rule's intent is to flag Accepted-despite-shortfall findings that are NOT documented; structurally well-formed but not substantively meaningful. Real-world V&V 40 cases (e.g., Nagaraja et al. 2024 §4) record the offsetting evidence here."
      }
    ]
  },
